TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Context-Dependent Model of the Gambling Effect
AU  - Bleichrodt, Han
AU  - Schmidt, Ulrich
Y1  - 2002/06/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.48.6.802.190
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.48.6.802.190
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 802
EP  - 812
VL  - 48
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper presents a context-dependent theory of decision under risk. The relevant contextual factor is the presence of a riskless lottery in a preference comparison. The theory only deviates from expected utility if the set of options contains both riskless and risky lotteries. The main motivation for the theory is to explain the gambling effect. Contrary to previous theories of the gambling effect, the present theory is consistent with stochastic dominance. It can, however, violate transitivity. The theory allows for a decomposition of the interaction between risk aversion and gambling aversion and thereby extends the classical Arrow-Pratt measure of risk aversion.
AB  - This paper presents a context-dependent theory of decision under risk. The relevant contextual factor is the presence of a riskless lottery in a preference comparison. The theory only deviates from expected utility if the set of options contains both riskless and risky lotteries. The main motivation for the theory is to explain the gambling effect. Contrary to previous theories of the gambling effect, the present theory is consistent with stochastic dominance. It can, however, violate transitivity. The theory allows for a decomposition of the interaction between risk aversion and gambling aversion and thereby extends the classical Arrow-Pratt measure of risk aversion.
